    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-30T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-30T13:00:00-05:00" n="622"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d622">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 <gloss target="#t_EW1"
                    >EW</gloss>/6–3045: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 622<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Washington Liaison Representative for the Delegation to
                        the Allied Commission on Reparations</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WJR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wolf</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Representative on the Allied Commission on
                        Reparations</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PEW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Pauley</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d622fn1">Sent over the signature of <persName
                            corresp="#p_GJC1">Grew</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-30T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 30, 1945—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1473. For <persName corresp="#p_PEW1">Pauley</persName> from <persName
                        corresp="#p_WJR1">Wolf</persName>.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DRK1">Ralph Davies</persName>
                    <gloss target="#t_PAW1">PAW</gloss> advises from best information available his
                    Program Division indicated 1946 surplus petroleum supplies in eastern European
                    areas under Russian occupation will be approximately 60,000 <gloss
                        target="#t_BD1">BD</gloss> over local requirements. Romania accounts [for]
                    47,000 <gloss target="#t_BD1">BD</gloss> this figure. At same time he advises
                    imports from Anglo-American sources to meet requirements western and
                    Mediterranean Europe will average approximately 292,000 <gloss target="#t_BD1"
                        >BD</gloss> last half [19]45 and 226,000 <gloss target="#t_BD1">BD</gloss>
                    [19]46. Any utilization apparent surplus eastern Europe not only eases critical
                    petroleum supply condition world wide but effects material transportation saving
                    if movement to western and Mediterranean Europe overland or from Constanta by
                    tanker initiated promptly. Sending under separate cover <persName
                        corresp="#p_DRK1">Davies</persName> letter and supporting tables.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d622fn2">Not printed. Cf. <ref target="#d626">document No.
                        626</ref>, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, and annex <hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >i</hi> to <ref target="frus1945Berlinv02#d1321">document No. 1321,
                            printed in vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>
                        </ref>.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
